Day 110 Overall – CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)
Final Day Before Exam

Today marked the final preparation day before taking the official Security+ exam scheduled for tomorrow morning. Focus was placed on reviewing multiple practice exams, reinforcing weak areas, and consolidating key concepts.

Practice Exam Results:

* Practice Exam 1: 60% (fatigue and difficult question set)
* Practice Exam 2: 85% (strong performance)
* Practice Exam 3: 50% (mental fatigue)
* Practice Exam 4: 65% (partial recovery)
* Final Quiz: 90% (9/10 correct)

Performance varied throughout the day due to mental fatigue and varying difficulty levels of question sources. However, strong scores in controlled environments indicate readiness for the exam.

Key Concepts Reviewed:

* Authentication & Identity:

  * Kerberos (ticket-based authentication, TGT)
  * TACACS+ vs RADIUS (authentication separation and encryption differences)
  * 802.1X / EAP negotiation process

* Security Architecture & Network Security:

  * Zero Trust model (verify every request, no implicit trust)
  * NAT and proxy use for anonymity and security
  * Screened subnet (DMZ) for isolating public-facing services
  * VLANs and segmentation concepts

* Cryptography & Protocols:

  * Diffie-Hellman key exchange
  * HMAC-SHA, SHA-256 hashing
  * TLS encryption negotiation
  * Self-encrypting drives (SED)

* Security Operations:

  * SIEM logging and real-time monitoring
  * Incident response process and escalation
  * Fail-closed vs fail-open systems
  * SCAP framework and CVSS scoring

* Risk & Compliance:

  * SOX, GLBA, and data protection regulations
  * Data classification levels and sensitivity
  * Compensating controls when primary controls are not feasible

* Attack Methods:

  * Brute force and hybrid attacks
  * Social engineering (steganography, insider threats)
  * Phishing targeting high-profile individuals

Lessons Learned:

* Overexposure to difficult or poorly structured practice questions negatively impacts confidence
* Timed practice exams provide a more accurate representation of readiness
* Understanding concepts is more effective than memorizing details
* Mental fatigue significantly affects performance and accuracy

Final Exam Plan:

* Exam scheduled for Saturday, March 28, 2026
* Check-in: 10:45 AM
* Start time: 11:15 AM

Strategy:

* Skip PBQs initially and return after completing multiple choice
* Eliminate incorrect answers first to narrow choices
* Avoid overthinking and trust initial instincts
* Focus on best practice and real-world application

Final Thoughts:
Preparation is complete. Consistent scores in the passing range demonstrate readiness. The focus now shifts from studying to execution.

Confidence is present, but success will depend on staying calm, managing time effectively, and trusting the preparation completed over the past several weeks.
